[{"sha":"b565087c5cd72fc222a0610011335a381d7f7ac7","author":{"name":"William Chargin","email":"366634280b879ce3c6c984f83d5675d046b04925@google.com"},"message":"Restrict scalar data class to `DT_FLOAT` tensors

Per [discussion on tensorflow/tensorboard#4352][1], we intend for the
scalar data class to only support f32 tensors. This is all that we’ve
written historically, and supporting “anything that can be cast to f32”
introduces more complexity that doesn’t seem justified.

[1]: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/4352#discussion_r528077811

[{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for

Change-Id: I115267447d5d9b906c51edb27513f4832dc97168","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/508374a893df7999633d9ebbe55e94d92eef7280"},{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

was that we were no longer specializing the sources in the examples.

This change specializes the sources using the TARGET, which appears to
be the only command line option that is needed.

sources (e.g. micro_speech/arduino/audio_provider.cc is used in the
output directory).

unzip prj/tensorflow_lite.zip
```

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for

[{"sha":"9a2150719b971adf078eca5cecbb18c146545cbd","author":{"name":"Sebastian Silbermann","email":"84fc128bc6cda84e77606b9e3bddd28c2b9ce031@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix prod build in ci/codesandbox (#20606)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/9a2150719b971adf078eca5cecbb18c146545cbd"},{"sha":"af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update DevTools to use getCacheForType API (#20548)

DevTools was built with a fork of an early idea for how Suspense cache might work. This idea is incompatible with newer APIs like `useTransition` which unfortunately prevented me from making certain UX improvements. This PR swaps out the primary usage of this cache (there are a few) in favor of the newer `unstable_getCacheForType` and `unstable_useCacheRefresh` APIs. We can go back and update the others in follow up PRs.

### Messaging changes

I've refactored the way the frontend loads component props/state/etc to hopefully make it better match the Suspense+cache model. Doing this gave up some of the small optimizations I'd added but hopefully the actual performance impact of that is minor and the overall ergonomic improvements of working with the cache API make this worth it.

The backend no longer remembers inspected paths. Instead, the frontend sends them every time and the backend sends a response with those paths. I've also added a new "force" parameter that the frontend can use to tell the backend to send a response even if the component hasn't rendered since the last time it asked. (This is used to get data for newly inspected paths.)

_Initial inspection..._
```
front |                                                      | back
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:true) ---------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes with no updates..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:false) --------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (no-change) -- |
```
_User clicks to expand a path, aka hydrate..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:true) ----> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes during which there is an update..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:false) ---> |
      | <----------------- "inspectedElement" (full-data) -- |
```

### Clear errors/warnings transition
Previously this meant there would be a delay after clicking the "clear" button. The UX after this change is much improved.

### Hydrating paths transition
I also added a transition to hydration (expanding "dehyrated" paths).

### Better error boundaries
I also added a lower-level error boundary in case the new suspense operation ever failed. It provides a better "retry" mechanism (select a new element) so DevTools doesn't become entirely useful. Here I'm intentionally causing an error every time I select an element.

### Improved snapshot tests
I also migrated several of the existing snapshot tests to use inline snapshots and added a new serializer for dehydrated props. Inline snapshots are easier to verify and maintain and the new serializer means dehydrated props will be formatted in a way that makes sense rather than being empty (in external snapshots) or super verbose (default inline snapshot format).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe"},{"sha":"ba9582da27481677cdac2dd000a438147a5df88e","author":{"name":"ChenLei","email":"2078e632128f17c4aa4e413d134a36c7418bccff@qq.com"},"message":"[devtools] Fix can't expand prop value in some scenario (#20534)

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/apshada/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

Change-Id: I115267447d5d9b906c51edb27513f4832dc97168","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/508374a893df7999633d9ebbe55e94d92eef7280"},{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

[{"sha":"212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Fix state migration remote version check

Previously the state migration process was using the fallback strict
error check when migrating to or from a Terraform Cloud workspace. This
resulted in an error when running init if the local and remote Terraform
versions did not exactly match.

This was excessively strict. When migrating from a remote Terraform
Cloud workspace to local state, there is no need for a version check at
all, as we cannot break the Terraform Cloud workspace. When migrating
to Terraform Cloud, we should use the more forgiving check, rather than
the strict equality.

This commit fixes both of these cases accordingly, and allows migrating
state to and from Terraform Cloud remote workspaces without errors.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/terraform/commits/212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818"},{"sha":"44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove InitProvisioner and close all at once

InitProvisioner only stored the provisioner in the cache and provided a
way to return an error. We can push this back further into the cli init
process, but for now we can move the error into the Provisioner call and
drop InitProvisioner.

This also changes CloseProvisioner to CloseProvisioners, in preparation
for the removal of the graph nodes.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/terraform/commits/44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68"},{"sha":"a6db207b8772cc874723b4d8100c9e19a51a8a3e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove provisioner graph nodes

Provisioners are always run via a single instance, and their
configuration and references are taken care of via their parent
resource, so there is no need to maintain the provisioner graph nodes.

The only action that will still need to be completed is calling the
Close method for external plugins. This was not consistently done with
the current handling of provisioners anyway, and we can now add that to
a single point with the new CloseProvisioners context method.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/terraform/commits/a6db207b8772cc874723b4d8100c9e19a51a8a3e"},{"sha":"fe7635f438c15458a88f95fdb80c0874c93f8f36","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"always close all provisioners after each walk

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JCofman/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

[{"sha":"a6b5256a29b60620bdeb9266d4935cb59cc1258e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Refactored recursive strict effects method to be iterative (#20642)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/a6b5256a29b60620bdeb9266d4935cb59cc1258e"},{"sha":"0fd6805c6d0477be917d31949a73b3bbdccfe71c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land rest of effects refactor in main fork (#20644)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/0fd6805c6d0477be917d31949a73b3bbdccfe71c"},{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

This fixes a panic when an admin specifies a custom default runtime,
when a plugin is started the shim config is nil.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742"},{"sha":"8086443a449af8ef5c5b0574de8957df7e52f296","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"docker info: silence unhandleable warnings

The following warnings in `docker info` are now discarded,
because there is no action user can actually take.

On cgroup v1:
- "WARNING: No blkio weight support"
- "WARNING: No blkio weight_device support"

On cgroup v2:
- "WARNING: No kernel memory TCP limit support"
- "WARNING: No oom kill disable support"

`docker run` still prints warnings when the missing feature is being attempted to use.

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/00225e220fb18283dcf9e4fa6625fad6746d8a50"},{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

We don't have a separate codepath to handle the internals of
AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat
empty strings as null strings within set objects to avoid the failed
assertions.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/060f8acc081c9be2ef5b2d0277742ea753615ee2"},{"sha":"527f3e654cfd2417410ae4bdeffecfa53d28ea7b","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26641 from hashicorp/jbardin/backport-26638

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353222879
Change-Id: I115267447d5d9b906c51edb27513f4832dc97168","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/508374a893df7999633d9ebbe55e94d92eef7280"},{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353222879
Change-Id: I115267447d5d9b906c51edb27513f4832dc97168","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/508374a893df7999633d9ebbe55e94d92eef7280"},{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

Change-Id: I535694f1fb244d7d367625b53af3c1734e469cc1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/3c84fc9a4def10a80dcf5901c57210d3562f13cd"},{"sha":"0c6169ff8c407aadd57cbf1c80cffec068991f0d","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix the source specialization for the examples.

With https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46473, we removed
support for TAGS on the makefile command line. An unintended consequence
was that we were no longer specializing the sources in the examples.

This change specializes the sources using the TARGET, which appears to
be the only command line option that is needed.

Manually confirmed that the generated arduino projects have the correct
sources (e.g. micro_speech/arduino/audio_provider.cc is used in the
output directory).

Test sequence:
```

Previously the state migration process was using the fallback strict
error check when migrating to or from a Terraform Cloud workspace. This
resulted in an error when running init if the local and remote Terraform
versions did not exactly match.

This was excessively strict. When migrating from a remote Terraform
Cloud workspace to local state, there is no need for a version check at
all, as we cannot break the Terraform Cloud workspace. When migrating
to Terraform Cloud, we should use the more forgiving check, rather than
the strict equality.

This commit fixes both of these cases accordingly, and allows migrating
state to and from Terraform Cloud remote workspaces without errors.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818"},{"sha":"44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove InitProvisioner and close all at once

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

[{"sha":"a6b5256a29b60620bdeb9266d4935cb59cc1258e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Refactored recursive strict effects method to be iterative (#20642)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kalecio/react/commits/a6b5256a29b60620bdeb9266d4935cb59cc1258e"},{"sha":"0fd6805c6d0477be917d31949a73b3bbdccfe71c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land rest of effects refactor in main fork (#20644)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kalecio/react/commits/0fd6805c6d0477be917d31949a73b3bbdccfe71c"},{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kalecio/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

With https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46473, we removed
support for TAGS on the makefile command line. An unintended consequence
was that we were no longer specializing the sources in the examples.

This change specializes the sources using the TARGET, which appears to
be the only command line option that is needed.

Manually confirmed that the generated arduino projects have the correct
sources (e.g. micro_speech/arduino/audio_provider.cc is used in the
output directory).

Test sequence:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=arduino OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn generate_arduino_zip
cd tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/arduino_x86_64_default
unzip prj/tensorflow_lite.zip
```

And then confirmed that the code in
```
tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/arduino_x86_64_default/tensorflow_lite/examples/micro_speech/arduino_audio_provider.cc matches
```

matches the code in:
```

With https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46473, we removed
support for TAGS on the makefile command line. An unintended consequence
was that we were no longer specializing the sources in the examples.

This change specializes the sources using the TARGET, which appears to
be the only command line option that is needed.

Manually confirmed that the generated arduino projects have the correct
sources (e.g. micro_speech/arduino/audio_provider.cc is used in the
output directory).

Test sequence:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=arduino OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn generate_arduino_zip
cd tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/arduino_x86_64_default
unzip prj/tensorflow_lite.zip
```

And then confirmed that the code in
```
tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/arduino_x86_64_default/tensorflow_lite/examples/micro_speech/arduino_audio_provider.cc matches
```

matches the code in:
```
tensorflow/lite/micro/examples/micro_speech/arduino/audio_provider.cc

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

Change-Id: I115267447d5d9b906c51edb27513f4832dc97168","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/508374a893df7999633d9ebbe55e94d92eef7280"},{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

Per [discussion on tensorflow/tensorboard#4352][1], we intend for the
scalar data class to only support f32 tensors. This is all that we’ve
written historically, and supporting “anything that can be cast to f32”
introduces more complexity that doesn’t seem justified.

[1]: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/4352#discussion_r528077811

[{"sha":"a6b5256a29b60620bdeb9266d4935cb59cc1258e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Refactored recursive strict effects method to be iterative (#20642)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/a6b5256a29b60620bdeb9266d4935cb59cc1258e"},{"sha":"0fd6805c6d0477be917d31949a73b3bbdccfe71c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land rest of effects refactor in main fork (#20644)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/0fd6805c6d0477be917d31949a73b3bbdccfe71c"},{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353222879
Change-Id: I115267447d5d9b906c51edb27513f4832dc97168","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/508374a893df7999633d9ebbe55e94d92eef7280"},{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

Change-Id: I115267447d5d9b906c51edb27513f4832dc97168","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/508374a893df7999633d9ebbe55e94d92eef7280"},{"sha":"2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Add a pass to reorder `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops.

This pass rewrites how data parallelism and model parallelism is expressed for resource inputs. It reorders `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` (model parallelism) and `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` (data parallelism) ops on resource inputs. It transforms a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` into a DAG where multiple `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops are feeding into a single `tf.TPUPartitionedInput`. Transforming the IR in such a manner will allow subsequent cluster formation pass to handle IR with both data and model parallelism in an easier manner.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353227403
Change-Id: I414289d7429af91282dc19e8d5d2452b0d58aa56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/2b69a2e56b1d871ec97c9324b1415ef230d760ae"},{"sha":"0de1c8c7a23b3951340c19c60d64a7a19804b175","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Handle pre-sharded resource inputs in TPUClusterFormation pass.

Resource variables might be pre-sharded using `tf.TPUPartitionedInput` op for model parallelism via XLA SPMD. When used in conjunction with data parallelism (using `tf.TPUReplicatedInput` ops) we must check for such pre-sharded inputs to the TPU cluster and move these ops within the `tf_device.replicate` body but outside the TPU cluster body.

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]
